%I A389624 #150 Jul 09 2026 15:28:32
%S A389624 1,2,10,25,45,71,104,142,186,237,294,356,425,500,580,667,761,859
%N A389624 Maximum number of regions that can be formed in the plane by drawing n lollipop (or qoppa) shapes of any size and orientation.
%C A389624 A lollipop or qoppa shape is a circle with a half-line attached to a point of the circle and extending from there in a radial direction to infinity.
%C A389624 The values a(0), ..., a(4) are due to Cutler-Karlsson-Sloane, the values a(5), a(6), a(7), a(10) are due to Paulsen, and the values a(8), a(9), a(11), ..., a(17) are due to Mahajan-Chopra.
%C A389624 Moreover, Mahajan-Chopra show that a(18) is 964 or 965, that a(19) = 1076, and that a(20) is 1193 or 1194. - _Matthias Paulsen_, Jun 05 2026
%H A389624 The Chordettes, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3rYoRaxgOE0">"Lollipop, lollipop, oh lolli, lolli, lolli, lollipop..."</a>, Youtube video, 2006.
%H A389624 David O. H. Cutler, Jonas Karlsson, and Neil J. A. Sloane, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.15864">Cutting a Pancake with an Exotic Knife</a>, arXiv:2511.15864[math.CO], v3, April 19 2026.
%H A389624 David O. H. Cutler, Jonas Karlsson, and Neil J. A. Sloane, Cutting a Pancake with an Exotic Knife, <a href="/A389624/a389624_2.jpg">Figure 39: Illustrating a(2) = 10</a>
%H A389624 David O. H. Cutler, Jonas Karlsson, and Neil J. A. Sloane, Cutting a Pancake with an Exotic Knife, <a href="/A389624/a389624_3.jpg">Figure 40: Illustrating a(3) = 25</a>
%H A389624 David O. H. Cutler, Jonas Karlsson, and Neil J. A. Sloane, Cutting a Pancake with an Exotic Knife, <a href="/A389624/a389624_5.jpg">Figure 41: Illustrating a(4) = 45</a>. The figure has 40 crossings and divides the plane into 45 regions.
%H A389624 Brady Haran and N. J. A. Sloane, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v8e-tYey7ts">The Unsolved Lollipop Problem</a>, Youtube/Numberphile video, June 2026.
%H A389624 Jonas Karlsson, <a href="/A389624/a389624_1.png">Illustrating a(4) = 45 (i)</a>. The figure has 40 crossings and divides the plane into 45 regions. In this view only three of the four lollipops are visible to the naked eye. The fourth lollipop is located where the three circles come together, as can be seen in the next link.
%H A389624 Jonas Karlsson, <a href="/A389624/a389624_2.png">Illustrating a(4) = 45 (ii)</a>. Closeup of the region where the three large circles come together. In this view the three large circles are so enormous that the intersections of the circles and their stems look like "T"s (the arcs of the circles appear to be straight lines).
%H A389624 Jonas Karlsson, <a href="/A389624/a389624_1.txt">Illustrating a(4) = 45 (iii)</a>. Python/mpmath code giving coordinates for the four lollipop arrangement.
%H A389624 Siddhartha Mahajan and Paras Chopra, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.06064">A Two-Graph Refinement of Paulsen's Lollipop Bounds</a>, arXiv:2606.06064[math.CO], 2026.
%H A389624 Matthias Paulsen, <a href="https://math.mp42.de/lollipop/">The Lollipop Problem</a>.
%H A389624 Siobhan Roberts, <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/20/science/infinite-pancake-math-puzzle.html?searchResultPosition=2">Infinite Pancakes, Anyone? A team of mathematicians seeks to cut an infinitely large pancake into as many pieces as possible, in a new take on an old puzzle.</a>, New York Times, Jan 20 2026.
%H A389624 N. J. A. Sloane, <a href="/A389624/a389624.pdf">The Lollipop Problem</a>, Dec. 25-26, 2025. [Superseded by the Cutler-Karlsson-Sloane and Paulsen  papers.]
